I don't think what I'm suggesting necessarily has to change the db schema as defined in the [db schema PR](https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi-service/pull/4611/files) at all.

I'm suggesting the API types look as follows:

We already have these structs:

```go
type CreatePolicyPackRequest struct {
    // Name is a unique URL-safe identifier (at the org level) for the package.
    // If the name has already been used by the organization, then the request will
    // create a new version of the Policy Pack (incremented by one). This is supplied
    // by the CLI.
    Name string `json:"name"`

    // A pretty name for the Policy Pack that is supplied by the package.
    DisplayName string `json:"displayName"`

    // The Policies outline the specific Policies in the package, and are derived
    // from the package by the CLI.
    Policies []Policy `json:"policies"`
}

// Policy defines the metadata for an individual Policy within a Policy Pack.
type Policy struct {
    // Unique URL-safe name for the policy.  This is unique to a specific version
    // of a Policy Pack.
    Name        string `json:"name"`
    DisplayName string `json:"displayName"`

    // Description is used to provide more context about the purpose of the policy.
    Description      string           `json:"description"`
    EnforcementLevel EnforcementLevel `json:"enforcementLevel"`

    // Message is the message that will be displayed to end users when they violate
    // this policy.
    Message string `json:"message"`
}
```

It seems very natural to include additional policy metadata on the `Policy` struct. I'm proposing we add an optional `ConfigSchema` property to `Policy` typed as a new `PolicyConfigSchema` struct:

```go
type Policy struct {
    ...

    // Optional config schema for the policy.
    ConfigSchema *PolicyConfigSchema `json:"configSchema,omitempty"`
}

type PolicyConfigSchema struct {
    // Config property name to JSON Schema map.
    Properties: map[string]*json.RawMessage `json:"properties,omitempty"`
    // Required config properties.
    Required:   []string                   `json:"required,omitempty"`
}
```

The `Properties` property is a map of config property names to their associated JSON schema.

The `Required` property is an array of required properties.

Now, in terms of the storage on the service side, if we want to store config schema information for the entire policy pack in a single column as a JSON blob, we still can. I'd suggest the service use a _simple_ JSON format similar to the following, rather than trying to synthesize an "uber JSON schema" for the entire policy pack. The service would just create a JSON document the looked as follows and store it as a blob in the db:

```JSON
{
    "a-policy-name": {
        "properties": {
            "kmsKeyId": {
                "type": "string",
                "description": "ARN of the KMS key used to encrypt the EFS file system."
            }
        }
    },
    "another-policy-name": {
        "properties": {
            "someRequiredProperty": {
                "type": "number",
                "description": "Some required property."
            }
        },
        "required": ["someRequiredProperty"]
    }
}
```

This JSON can be returned to the front-end, and it'd be very easy for the front-end to drill into each policy's config properties.

Though, we may want to structure the response to the front-end a bit more nicely in the `apitype`, making use of the proposed `PolicyConfigSchema` struct, something like:

```go
 // GetPolicyPackConfigSchemaResponse is the response that includes the JSON
 // of a particular Policy Pack's configuration.
 type GetPolicyPackConfigSchemaResponse struct {
 	// Map of policy name to config schema.
 	ConfigSchema: map[string] PolicyConfigSchema `json:"configSchema,omitempty"`
 }
```

Of course, if we wanted to add more structure in the DB we could consider adding something like a `PolicyConfigPropertiesSchema` table that references the `Policies` table, but I don't think we need to bother doing that right now as it seems more ceremony than it's worth.

